00:02:19.930 --> 00:02:21.570
So as Terry said,
I was brought up

00:02:21.570 --> 00:02:24.510
in Elmira, New York,
a very small town

00:02:24.510 --> 00:02:26.580
in the middle of New York State.

00:02:26.580 --> 00:02:29.490
And my dream was to
be a football player.

00:02:29.490 --> 00:02:33.000
But while I was 17 years
old, my coach pulled me along

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:37.110
on the sidelines and said, look,
I don't think you should play.

00:02:37.110 --> 00:02:39.070
And I said, what do you mean?

00:02:39.070 --> 00:02:41.430
And he said, look,
you know, the linemen

00:02:41.430 --> 00:02:45.630
average about 200
pounds each, and you

00:02:45.630 --> 00:02:47.940
weigh about 100, 110 pounds.

00:02:47.940 --> 00:02:50.130
I don't think it's a good idea.

00:02:50.130 --> 00:02:55.110
So I decided to step back
and do something else.

00:02:55.110 --> 00:02:58.320
So I got a job in a
sporting goods store.

00:02:58.320 --> 00:03:00.450
And as I was working in
this sporting goods store,

00:03:00.450 --> 00:03:02.280
I was learning about retail.

00:03:02.280 --> 00:03:04.380
And at that point
in time, my dream

00:03:04.380 --> 00:03:06.450
was to have my own retail store.

00:03:06.450 --> 00:03:10.110
But I wanted to sell cool
clothes in my retail store.

00:03:10.110 --> 00:03:14.040
So I took my $150 I'd
saved from working

00:03:14.040 --> 00:03:17.610
part time in the
sporting shop, and a gas

00:03:17.610 --> 00:03:20.310
station in the nighttime,
in the evenings,

00:03:20.310 --> 00:03:24.270
and I drove my Volkswagen
Bug to New York City.

00:03:24.270 --> 00:03:26.190
I bought 20 pairs
of bell-bottom jeans

00:03:26.190 --> 00:03:28.170
from the streets
of New York City,

00:03:28.170 --> 00:03:30.420
put them in the
backseat of my car,

00:03:30.420 --> 00:03:32.310
drove them to the
school parking lot,

00:03:32.310 --> 00:03:34.650
and started selling
bell-bottoms to my friends

00:03:34.650 --> 00:03:38.800
and my classmates, who had
never seen bell-bottoms before.

00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:41.640
So that really triggered
my initial interest

00:03:41.640 --> 00:03:43.620
in opening a jeans shop.

00:03:43.620 --> 00:03:45.420
And I opened a jeans
shop when I was

00:03:45.420 --> 00:03:50.610
18 called People's Place in
downtown Elmira, in a basement.

00:03:50.610 --> 00:03:51.750
I painted it black.

00:03:51.750 --> 00:03:53.730
I played rock and roll music.

00:03:53.730 --> 00:03:55.740
And all of my
friends from school,

00:03:55.740 --> 00:03:58.050
at 3 o'clock in the
afternoon, when the bell rang,

00:03:58.050 --> 00:04:01.710
would march to People's Place
and buy clothes from me.

00:04:01.710 --> 00:04:04.380
Within a year, I
started expanding,

00:04:04.380 --> 00:04:07.230
and I opened another store
on the Cornell campus.

00:04:07.230 --> 00:04:09.390
And what I learned
at that point in time

00:04:09.390 --> 00:04:12.330
was that my reach was not
just in Elmira, New York,

00:04:12.330 --> 00:04:13.800
but it was beyond.

00:04:13.800 --> 00:04:17.940
So I always had a dream of
expanding beyond my roots

00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:22.780
and expanding beyond just my
hometown of Elmira, New York.

00:04:22.780 --> 00:04:26.370
And while I was expanding into
other college towns in New York

00:04:26.370 --> 00:04:29.640
State, I realized there was
an international customer

00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:31.710
and a fashion
customer who really

00:04:31.710 --> 00:04:33.180
liked what I was selling.

00:04:33.180 --> 00:04:36.810
But I was really never
satisfied buying merchandise

00:04:36.810 --> 00:04:38.820
from manufacturers,
because I always

00:04:38.820 --> 00:04:42.060
thought I could do better at
designing the clothes if I

00:04:42.060 --> 00:04:43.530
could do it myself.

00:04:43.530 --> 00:04:45.480
So one day, I took
a pad and a pen,

00:04:45.480 --> 00:04:48.510
and I started sketching
clothes I would want to wear

00:04:48.510 --> 00:04:51.690
and clothes I wanted
my customers to wear.

00:04:51.690 --> 00:04:54.780
So my relatives and friends
told me I was crazy.

00:04:54.780 --> 00:04:57.480
There was no way I could
ever become a designer

00:04:57.480 --> 00:05:00.060
or manufacture
clothes, because you

00:05:00.060 --> 00:05:03.460
needed to know how
to cut patterns,

00:05:03.460 --> 00:05:07.050
and you needed a lot of
money and connections.

00:05:07.050 --> 00:05:09.520
And you really wouldn't
be able to do that.

00:05:09.520 --> 00:05:13.290
But I hired local seamstresses
to sew jeans for me.

00:05:13.290 --> 00:05:15.480
And when they would
sew the genes,

00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:17.900
I took them to the
local laundromat,

00:05:17.900 --> 00:05:22.320
and I put sticks and stones and
bricks and Clorox and all sorts

00:05:22.320 --> 00:05:25.080
of treatments into
the washing machines

00:05:25.080 --> 00:05:28.410
and bleached them, distressed
them, made them stone-washed,

00:05:28.410 --> 00:05:31.770
made them look used
and old, but very cool.

00:05:31.770 --> 00:05:34.950
So although the local laundromat
wouldn't allow me to come back

00:05:34.950 --> 00:05:38.190
in after a few
visits, I thought it

00:05:38.190 --> 00:05:41.760
was incredible to invent
something different and new

00:05:41.760 --> 00:05:43.470
for the consumer.

00:05:43.470 --> 00:05:45.390
So I kept designing.

00:05:45.390 --> 00:05:48.930
And I kept putting
these ideas on paper.

00:05:48.930 --> 00:05:51.450
And during this
time, my parents were

00:05:51.450 --> 00:05:52.950
begging me to go to college.

00:05:52.950 --> 00:05:55.200
I was fighting with
them like crazy.

00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:57.840
And I really just
wanted to be on my own,

00:05:57.840 --> 00:05:59.610
in business on my own.

00:05:59.610 --> 00:06:02.160
And one day, my
accountant came to me

00:06:02.160 --> 00:06:05.172
and basically told
me I was bankrupt.

00:06:05.172 --> 00:06:06.630
And I said, well,
what do you mean?

00:06:06.630 --> 00:06:09.882
Can't we just take a bank
loan to pay off the debt?

00:06:09.882 --> 00:06:11.340
He said, no, no,
no, you've already

00:06:11.340 --> 00:06:13.140
borrowed money from this bank.

00:06:13.140 --> 00:06:17.430
And you either have to
close or file Chapter 11.

00:06:17.430 --> 00:06:19.770
I didn't even know
what Chapter 11 was.

00:06:19.770 --> 00:06:22.050
So that was really
my college education.

00:06:22.050 --> 00:06:25.320
It was cold water,
a slap in the face.

00:06:25.320 --> 00:06:28.080
And it taught me that
I actually should

00:06:28.080 --> 00:06:31.410
have gone to school
to learn economics

00:06:31.410 --> 00:06:35.220
and to learn all I could learn
about business before going

00:06:35.220 --> 00:06:36.090
into business.

00:06:36.090 --> 00:06:38.100
But I put the cart
before the horse.

00:06:38.100 --> 00:06:41.160
So I had to take a step
backwards to go forward.

00:06:41.160 --> 00:06:45.060
I did end up teaching myself
how to read a balance sheet,

00:06:45.060 --> 00:06:47.940
and how to understand
the aspects of business,

00:06:47.940 --> 00:06:51.300
and what the business end of
the business was all about.

00:06:51.300 --> 00:06:55.440
And I started to actually
formulate a small company.

00:06:55.440 --> 00:06:58.230
I formulated a company
called Tommy Hill.

00:06:58.230 --> 00:07:02.010
And I manufactured clothes
locally and sold them

00:07:02.010 --> 00:07:05.340
to Macy's, Bloomingdale's,
the Gap-- at the time,

00:07:05.340 --> 00:07:07.200
they bought many
different brands.

00:07:07.200 --> 00:07:13.770
And I actually went into
business on my own in 1984.

00:07:13.770 --> 00:07:16.290
After some starts and
stops, because I found out

00:07:16.290 --> 00:07:18.330
the Tommy Hill name
was registered,

00:07:18.330 --> 00:07:20.320
I was fortunate
enough to meet a man

00:07:20.320 --> 00:07:23.200
by the name of Mohan
Murjani, who, at the time,

00:07:23.200 --> 00:07:25.720
owned Gloria Vanderbilt jeans.

00:07:25.720 --> 00:07:29.080
He asked if I would
come to work for him

00:07:29.080 --> 00:07:31.622
and develop a Tommy
Hilfiger brand.

00:07:31.622 --> 00:07:33.580
And I said, well, you
know, I'd really love to,

00:07:33.580 --> 00:07:37.660
but I just took a job
with Calvin Klein.

00:07:37.660 --> 00:07:41.640
Calvin Klein had offered me a
job to design their jeanswear.

00:07:41.640 --> 00:07:44.080
And I thought I was
floating in heaven.

00:07:44.080 --> 00:07:46.120
I couldn't believe
I was actually

00:07:46.120 --> 00:07:50.770
asked by Calvin Klein
himself to design his line.

00:07:50.770 --> 00:07:52.750
And I had accepted the job.

00:07:52.750 --> 00:07:55.660
So this was a Thursday-- I
promised the Calvin Klein

00:07:55.660 --> 00:07:57.490
people I would be
on a plane going

00:07:57.490 --> 00:08:01.990
to the Orient on the following
Monday-- when Mr. Murjani said,

00:08:01.990 --> 00:08:04.270
go into competition
with Calvin Klein.

00:08:04.270 --> 00:08:05.410
I will back you.

00:08:05.410 --> 00:08:06.640
I have factories.

00:08:06.640 --> 00:08:07.780
I'll support you.

00:08:07.780 --> 00:08:09.932
And we'll develop
Tommy Hilfiger.

00:08:09.932 --> 00:08:11.890
And I said, but you know,
Tommy Hilfiger people

00:08:11.890 --> 00:08:13.690
can't even pronounce the name.

00:08:13.690 --> 00:08:16.300
And he said, do you think
people can pronounce Yves Saint

00:08:16.300 --> 00:08:17.750
Laurent?

00:08:17.750 --> 00:08:19.345
And I said, well,
you've got a point.

00:08:19.345 --> 00:08:21.880
And he said, look, why
don't you call Calvin,

00:08:21.880 --> 00:08:25.780
tell him that you've
accepted another position.

00:08:25.780 --> 00:08:28.810
So with a little bit of
coaxing, a lot of excitement,

00:08:28.810 --> 00:08:31.480
I ended up calling Calvin
Klein and telling Calvin

00:08:31.480 --> 00:08:33.789
that I was going into
competition with him.

00:08:33.789 --> 00:08:36.610
And this was in 1985,
after he had been

00:08:36.610 --> 00:08:38.409
established for many years.

00:08:38.409 --> 00:08:42.669
And he basically laughed, and
then hung up the phone on me.

00:08:42.669 --> 00:08:44.350
So we started Tommy Hilfiger.

00:08:44.350 --> 00:08:46.360
And when I started
Tommy Hilfiger,

00:08:46.360 --> 00:08:49.960
I decided to design
what I wanted to wear,

00:08:49.960 --> 00:08:52.810
what I thought was missing
in the marketplace.

00:08:52.810 --> 00:08:55.390
And what was missing,
in my opinion,

00:08:55.390 --> 00:08:58.570
was a cool, preppy brand.

00:08:58.570 --> 00:09:01.566
There was a Brooks Brothers,
and there was a Ralph Lauren,

00:09:01.566 --> 00:09:03.190
and there were preppy
brands out there.

00:09:03.190 --> 00:09:06.190
But they were very
boring and very staid.

00:09:06.190 --> 00:09:09.670
I decided to make
them very cool.

00:09:09.670 --> 00:09:13.190
So I redesigned all
of the preppy clothes

00:09:13.190 --> 00:09:15.970
I had been brought up wearing--
the button-down shirt,

00:09:15.970 --> 00:09:20.920
the chino trouser, the cotton
sweater, a basic khaki golf

00:09:20.920 --> 00:09:22.180
jacket.

00:09:22.180 --> 00:09:24.610
And I redesigned
them to make them

00:09:24.610 --> 00:09:26.500
be more relevant for the time.

00:09:26.500 --> 00:09:29.320
I wanted them to be
relaxed, oversized,

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:34.550
fun, colorful, detailed, but
to have a cool edge with them.

00:09:34.550 --> 00:09:37.480
And at this point
in time, I actually

00:09:37.480 --> 00:09:41.890
put them in a duffel bag
myself, went to Bloomingdale's,

00:09:41.890 --> 00:09:44.500
Neiman's, Saks-- all
the department stores--

00:09:44.500 --> 00:09:47.410
knocked on the doors,
and I sold my collection

00:09:47.410 --> 00:09:48.640
into these stores.

00:09:48.640 --> 00:09:51.520
And that is where I met Mr.
Terry Lundgren, when he was--

00:09:51.520 --> 00:09:55.180
actually, Terry was at
Bullocks before Neiman's.

00:09:55.180 --> 00:09:58.870
But I was out on the
road selling my clothes

00:09:58.870 --> 00:10:02.410
to people like Terry,
who were, I think,

00:10:02.410 --> 00:10:06.910
kind enough and open
enough to, at least, sample

00:10:06.910 --> 00:10:07.900
what I was selling.

00:10:07.900 --> 00:10:09.160
And it ended up selling.

00:10:09.160 --> 00:10:12.310
The customers ended
up accepting my

00:10:12.310 --> 00:10:15.070
look-- my preppy,
all-American, classic look.

00:10:15.070 --> 00:10:17.020
So I started to expand it.

00:10:17.020 --> 00:10:20.920
And in 1989, Mr. Murjani
came to me and said, look,

00:10:20.920 --> 00:10:24.400
I just took the license
for Coca-Cola clothes.

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:26.170
Would you help me design it?

00:10:26.170 --> 00:10:27.760
And I said, Coca-Cola clothes?

00:10:27.760 --> 00:10:30.490
I mean, that seems
a little weird.

00:10:30.490 --> 00:10:32.770
And he said, well,
look, if you really

00:10:32.770 --> 00:10:35.680
want me to continue to support
you with Tommy Hilfiger,

00:10:35.680 --> 00:10:38.860
I need your help designing
Coca-Cola clothes.

00:10:38.860 --> 00:10:41.230
So I went back to
my drawing board.

00:10:41.230 --> 00:10:44.440
And I thought, OK, if I were
to wear Coca-Cola clothes, what

00:10:44.440 --> 00:10:45.940
would they look like?

00:10:45.940 --> 00:10:49.420
And at first, I envisioned a red
T-shirt with a white Coca-Cola

00:10:49.420 --> 00:10:50.290
printing.

00:10:50.290 --> 00:10:51.850
And I said, no,
that wouldn't work.

00:10:51.850 --> 00:10:55.750
So I decided to design great,
cool, American-classic clothes,

00:10:55.750 --> 00:10:58.630
and then put the
Coca-Cola label on them.

00:10:58.630 --> 00:11:00.580
So we developed
Coca-Cola clothes

00:11:00.580 --> 00:11:03.110
in the '80s and early '90s.

00:11:03.110 --> 00:11:07.300
And it was an explosive
business right out of the box.

00:11:07.300 --> 00:11:09.580
But within two years,
it took a tumble.

00:11:09.580 --> 00:11:13.300
And what that taught me
was that trends never last.

00:11:13.300 --> 00:11:17.890
And I would have to develop a
real brand, avoiding trends,

00:11:17.890 --> 00:11:20.330
but being true to myself.

00:11:20.330 --> 00:11:23.560
So I continued to build my
preppy, all-American, classic

00:11:23.560 --> 00:11:24.490
look.

00:11:24.490 --> 00:11:27.400
I took on some new
partners in the early '90s.

00:11:27.400 --> 00:11:32.540
And these partners
were from Ralph Lauren.

00:11:32.540 --> 00:11:34.570
A couple of them owned
Ralph Lauren in Europe.

00:11:34.570 --> 00:11:38.050
One was and is a
Chinese manufacturer.

00:11:38.050 --> 00:11:40.630
And the other was, at
the time, the president

00:11:40.630 --> 00:11:42.850
of Gloria Vanderbilt
with Murjani.

00:11:42.850 --> 00:11:44.650
So they had some experience.

00:11:44.650 --> 00:11:47.050
And we sat around
one day and decided

00:11:47.050 --> 00:11:48.940
what to do with the brand.

00:11:48.940 --> 00:11:51.910
And they said, Tommy,
what is the real vision?

00:11:51.910 --> 00:11:56.800
And I said, I want to
build a global lifestyle

00:11:56.800 --> 00:12:00.010
brand with a preppy attitude.

00:12:00.010 --> 00:12:06.310
But I wanted to be aspirational,
inspirational, exciting, fun,

00:12:06.310 --> 00:12:11.690
style-wise, on point,
fresh, new, and unique.

00:12:11.690 --> 00:12:12.820
So we did that.

00:12:12.820 --> 00:12:16.480
And we did it over a
period of 20-some years.

00:12:16.480 --> 00:12:18.520
And as I said, this
is the 25th year,

00:12:18.520 --> 00:12:21.790
so it was 20-some years
since this new partnership.

00:12:21.790 --> 00:12:25.420
And we developed a classic,
all-American, preppy, global

00:12:25.420 --> 00:12:26.980
lifestyle brand.

