Men's wear, women's wear,
children's wear, fragrance,

00:12:30.220 --> 00:12:35.500
accessories, neckwear, dress
shirts, shoes, belts, bags.

00:12:35.500 --> 00:12:37.150
We developed homewear.

00:12:37.150 --> 00:12:40.750
So it was really coming around
to becoming a global lifestyle

00:12:40.750 --> 00:12:41.620
brand.

00:12:41.620 --> 00:12:45.020
Well, we weren't really
global quite yet.

00:12:45.020 --> 00:12:48.370
We had a store in London,
and we had a small selling

00:12:48.370 --> 00:12:51.220
office in the middle
of Europe in Amsterdam.

00:12:51.220 --> 00:12:54.010
And the selling office
was run by a man

00:12:54.010 --> 00:12:58.060
by the name of Fred Gehring,
who is currently our CEO.

00:12:58.060 --> 00:13:02.800
Fred's idea was to expand
the brand throughout Europe

00:13:02.800 --> 00:13:07.900
to become a luxury,
upscale lifestyle brand.

00:13:07.900 --> 00:13:11.890
Slowly but surely, while we're
expanding rapidly in the United

00:13:11.890 --> 00:13:15.130
States, opening shops
and department stores,

00:13:15.130 --> 00:13:19.910
advertising, marketing through
celebrity, through music,

00:13:19.910 --> 00:13:23.860
through all sorts of unique
ways, sponsoring racing teams,

00:13:23.860 --> 00:13:28.030
sailing racing, we were
developing nautical clothes

00:13:28.030 --> 00:13:32.020
and dressing some of
the America's Cup teams.

00:13:32.020 --> 00:13:36.180
We were developing clothes
for Formula One race drivers,

00:13:36.180 --> 00:13:39.550
and really touching society,
touching pop culture

00:13:39.550 --> 00:13:40.810
and society.

00:13:40.810 --> 00:13:44.320
When it was time to launch
our Tommy and Tommy Girl

00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:47.980
fragrances, I said, I think
we should attach ourselves

00:13:47.980 --> 00:13:49.030
to music.

00:13:49.030 --> 00:13:51.610
Because music, when I opened
my People's Place store

00:13:51.610 --> 00:13:55.160
in the very beginning,
was my inspiration.

00:13:55.160 --> 00:13:58.760
At that time, when I
was 17 and 18 years old,

00:13:58.760 --> 00:14:01.640
my friends and I wanted to
look like the rock stars,

00:14:01.640 --> 00:14:03.130
wearing bell bottoms.

00:14:03.130 --> 00:14:04.190
We had long hair.

00:14:04.190 --> 00:14:07.790
We listened to the Beatles, the
Rolling Stones, Jimi Hendrix--

00:14:07.790 --> 00:14:10.070
all of that classic rock music.

00:14:10.070 --> 00:14:11.900
And the music was
great, but we wanted

00:14:11.900 --> 00:14:13.670
to look like the rock stars.

00:14:13.670 --> 00:14:19.280
And that really inspired
me to develop my own stores

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:22.380
and go into the
fashion business.

00:14:22.380 --> 00:14:25.670
So here we are in the '90s,
developing a new fragrance.

00:14:25.670 --> 00:14:30.140
And we said, what can we do to
be unique in our advertising

00:14:30.140 --> 00:14:31.290
and marketing?

00:14:31.290 --> 00:14:34.520
So I decided to hire
the sons and daughters

00:14:34.520 --> 00:14:36.710
of all the iconic rock stars.

00:14:36.710 --> 00:14:40.820
We hired Mick Jagger's son and
daughter, Sting's daughter,

00:14:40.820 --> 00:14:43.880
Rod Stewart's daughter,
Quincy Jones' daughter,

00:14:43.880 --> 00:14:47.570
and we put them all in a
group in an advertisement

00:14:47.570 --> 00:14:49.760
for Tommy and Tommy
Girl fragrance.

00:14:49.760 --> 00:14:52.670
And our fragrances
took off like crazy.

00:14:52.670 --> 00:14:57.230
At that point in time, I thought
it was a good idea to market

00:14:57.230 --> 00:14:59.720
through celebrity,
because I thought

00:14:59.720 --> 00:15:02.060
that, if the celebrities
wore the clothes,

00:15:02.060 --> 00:15:04.430
their fans would also
wear the clothes.

00:15:04.430 --> 00:15:06.410
So we started
dressing Lenny Kravitz

00:15:06.410 --> 00:15:10.430
and sponsored a Lenny Kravitz
tour, a Sheryl Crow tour.

00:15:10.430 --> 00:15:13.640
We used David Bowie and
Iman in our advertising.

00:15:13.640 --> 00:15:18.830
We used everyone from the
Rolling Stones in a sponsorship

00:15:18.830 --> 00:15:22.550
concert tour to Britney Spears.

00:15:22.550 --> 00:15:24.440
And I remember
the day my brother

00:15:24.440 --> 00:15:26.690
Andy brought me Britney Spears.

00:15:26.690 --> 00:15:29.510
He said, Britney
is a new musician.

00:15:29.510 --> 00:15:30.860
She just moved to New York.

00:15:30.860 --> 00:15:33.830
And she has a hit coming
out on the radio any day.

00:15:33.830 --> 00:15:37.040
And wouldn't it be great to use
her in our jeans advertising?

00:15:37.040 --> 00:15:40.190
So we used her in our
Tommy jeans advertising

00:15:40.190 --> 00:15:45.920
the day her Baby One More
Time hit went to number one.

00:15:45.920 --> 00:15:48.410
We had no idea who
she was at that time.

00:15:48.410 --> 00:15:50.630
But we were deciding,
at that point in time,

00:15:50.630 --> 00:15:53.840
to market and advertise
through celebrity,

00:15:53.840 --> 00:15:55.910
which is done all the time now.

00:15:55.910 --> 00:15:58.220
But I think it's
probably something that

00:15:58.220 --> 00:16:01.730
is overused today and overdone.

00:16:01.730 --> 00:16:04.130
So I'm always looking for
something new and something

00:16:04.130 --> 00:16:07.670
different, something unique,
but holding onto the brand

00:16:07.670 --> 00:16:09.950
and keeping true to its roots.

00:16:09.950 --> 00:16:12.080
Recently, as you
saw in the video,

00:16:12.080 --> 00:16:17.300
we developed a family campaign--
an all-American, quirky, fun

00:16:17.300 --> 00:16:18.830
family campaign.

00:16:18.830 --> 00:16:22.040
And that really
plants us into who

00:16:22.040 --> 00:16:24.890
we are, because we
are a family brand.

00:16:24.890 --> 00:16:28.320
We're a cool,
American-classic family brand.

00:16:28.320 --> 00:16:33.140
And it all happens as a result
of having a great product.

00:16:33.140 --> 00:16:36.650
At the end of the day, I believe
you can have the greatest

00:16:36.650 --> 00:16:40.550
advertising, the most
amazing logo, the greatest

00:16:40.550 --> 00:16:43.460
name, the most marketing
muscle, but if you

00:16:43.460 --> 00:16:46.790
don't have the product, you
absolutely have nothing.

00:16:46.790 --> 00:16:50.000
So our focus, at
this point in time,

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:52.010
as it was in the
very beginning, is

00:16:52.010 --> 00:16:56.750
to offer the consumer amazing
product, amazing value,

00:16:56.750 --> 00:17:01.790
affordable, accessible,
inspirational, aspirational.

00:17:01.790 --> 00:17:03.710
And that's what
we're really focused

00:17:03.710 --> 00:17:06.020
on more than anything else.

00:17:06.020 --> 00:17:08.760
Although we are opening
stores all over the world.

00:17:08.760 --> 00:17:12.079
We have over 1,000 stores
in the world today.

00:17:12.079 --> 00:17:15.440
We just opened a new store on
Fifth Avenue in New York City.

00:17:15.440 --> 00:17:20.060
We have a new flagship store
in Paris on the Champs-Elysees.

00:17:20.060 --> 00:17:26.180
We're opening a new flagship in
Tokyo, in Rio, in Buenos Aires.

00:17:26.180 --> 00:17:28.490
We just opened in
Dublin recently.

00:17:28.490 --> 00:17:31.820
We believe having our own
stores is very important.

00:17:31.820 --> 00:17:34.820
But we also believe in
having a relationship

00:17:34.820 --> 00:17:38.090
and a partnership with a
department store like Macy's is

00:17:38.090 --> 00:17:39.920
incredibly important.

00:17:39.920 --> 00:17:42.410
Because with this
exclusive arrangement,

00:17:42.410 --> 00:17:45.500
we have a true
family partnership,

00:17:45.500 --> 00:17:48.980
where we have shops-- men's,
women's, children's-- in all

00:17:48.980 --> 00:17:50.510
of the Macy's stores.

00:17:50.510 --> 00:17:52.670
And we don't have
to focus on selling

00:17:52.670 --> 00:17:55.640
25 or 50 different
customers in the US.

00:17:55.640 --> 00:17:58.880
We focus on a
partnership with Macy's.

00:17:58.880 --> 00:18:02.690
And our business, as Terry
said, has never been better.

00:18:02.690 --> 00:18:04.290
And it continues to grow.

00:18:04.290 --> 00:18:08.720
We continue to add new product
lines, new ideas, new marketing

00:18:08.720 --> 00:18:14.840
ideas, and continue to evolve
the business into the future.

00:18:14.840 --> 00:18:17.570
All of that keeps me very busy.

00:18:17.570 --> 00:18:20.270
As a matter of
fact, for me, it's

00:18:20.270 --> 00:18:21.980
not like work at
all because it's

00:18:21.980 --> 00:18:24.260
so much fun and so exciting.

00:18:24.260 --> 00:18:27.200
But in addition to
that, we're, I think,

00:18:27.200 --> 00:18:29.720
charity-minded, as
you [? could ?] say.

00:18:29.720 --> 00:18:32.960
We're very involved
in youth outreach

00:18:32.960 --> 00:18:36.350
programs like the Fresh
Air Fund in New York City.

00:18:36.350 --> 00:18:40.650
We built a summer camp for
the underprivileged children.

00:18:40.650 --> 00:18:43.700
We've been involved
in helping raise funds

00:18:43.700 --> 00:18:46.370
and building the
Martin Luther King Jr.

00:18:46.370 --> 00:18:48.840
Memorial in Washington DC.

00:18:48.840 --> 00:18:53.750
We're involved with breast
cancer, Evelyn Lauder's quest

00:18:53.750 --> 00:18:56.040
to fight breast cancer.

00:18:56.040 --> 00:18:59.310
We're involved with MS,
the race to erase MS.

00:18:59.310 --> 00:19:01.410
