00:26:16.820 --> 00:26:18.860
You've never
bastardized your name.

00:26:18.860 --> 00:26:21.710
You've always kept
this new luxury going

00:26:21.710 --> 00:26:23.420
with your entire collection.

00:26:23.420 --> 00:26:26.120
That's hard for a lot of
companies and brands today.

00:26:26.120 --> 00:26:27.470
So how do you maintain it?

00:26:27.470 --> 00:26:31.190
Or what is always your criteria
for being aspirational,

00:26:31.190 --> 00:26:35.480
quality, and so image-oriented?

00:26:35.480 --> 00:26:37.450
I think it's a
very good question.

00:26:37.450 --> 00:26:41.740
Actually, in the mid-'90s,
I made a big mistake.

00:26:41.740 --> 00:26:43.950
We overexpanded.

00:26:43.950 --> 00:26:47.910
And we created more supply
than there was demand.

00:26:47.910 --> 00:26:49.890
As a result of that, we
had to take a big step

00:26:49.890 --> 00:26:51.750
backwards to go forward.

00:26:51.750 --> 00:26:53.910
And that taught us a lesson.

00:26:53.910 --> 00:27:00.210
And the lesson was that to
keep it somewhat exclusive

00:27:00.210 --> 00:27:05.070
is important-- to somehow
be on the other side

00:27:05.070 --> 00:27:09.090
of the supply-demand equation.

00:27:09.090 --> 00:27:11.340
Because once you
oversupply the demand,

00:27:11.340 --> 00:27:14.640
you have a glut of product
in the marketplace,

00:27:14.640 --> 00:27:16.830
and the customer says, no more.

00:27:16.830 --> 00:27:20.740
So it is, I think,
always a challenge.

00:27:20.740 --> 00:27:23.580
It's something we're
looking at every single day.

00:27:23.580 --> 00:27:25.920
But I really believe
that there is

00:27:25.920 --> 00:27:30.630
such a thing as overexpanding
and damaging the brand.

00:27:30.630 --> 00:27:34.080
We really experienced,
I would say,

00:27:34.080 --> 00:27:36.210
a brush with it in the '90s.

00:27:36.210 --> 00:27:41.770
Fortunately, our management
team acted upon it very quickly.

00:27:41.770 --> 00:27:44.250
We cleaned up
distribution, so to speak.

00:27:44.250 --> 00:27:47.910
We were selling all of
our excess to discounters.

00:27:47.910 --> 00:27:49.890
And we put an end to that.

00:27:49.890 --> 00:27:53.400
And we do have some of
our own outlet stores.

00:27:53.400 --> 00:27:56.400
But we are always
looking at the balance,

00:27:56.400 --> 00:28:01.260
and always making sure that we
don't overexpand and over-flood

00:28:01.260 --> 00:28:03.750
the market with our
product, because it takes

00:28:03.750 --> 00:28:05.590
the value out of the product.

00:28:05.590 --> 00:28:06.090
Perfect.

00:28:06.090 --> 00:28:08.520
And then how would you
describe new luxury today?

00:28:08.520 --> 00:28:10.560
What is new luxury
for the consumer?

00:28:10.560 --> 00:28:14.040
New luxury today, for me and
for the consumer, I believe,

00:28:14.040 --> 00:28:15.840
is affordable luxury.

00:28:15.840 --> 00:28:18.510
Because people want
luxury, but people

00:28:18.510 --> 00:28:20.050
want to be able to afford it.

00:28:20.050 --> 00:28:22.950
And in years past, luxury
was something that you really

00:28:22.950 --> 00:28:24.660
couldn't quite afford.

00:28:24.660 --> 00:28:29.280
It was always a tremendous
reach to buy something cashmere

00:28:29.280 --> 00:28:34.230
or something from one
of the luxury brands.

00:28:34.230 --> 00:28:36.720
But I think it's
up to us to offer

00:28:36.720 --> 00:28:41.040
that customer great luxury
at affordable price points.

00:28:41.040 --> 00:28:44.430
Because everyone
wants it, and everyone

00:28:44.430 --> 00:28:47.910
feels that they're
deserving of it somehow.

00:28:47.910 --> 00:28:50.970
And whether it's a
cashmere cotton sweater,

00:28:50.970 --> 00:28:58.500
or whether it is a
handbag with a bit of trim

00:28:58.500 --> 00:29:06.480
from either a lizard or snake
or fur, just to, I would say,

00:29:06.480 --> 00:29:08.130
make the customer
feel that they're

00:29:08.130 --> 00:29:09.390
getting something luxurious.

00:29:09.390 --> 00:29:11.130
I think that's very
important to do.

00:29:11.130 --> 00:29:13.170
I know Macy's is
working on that.

00:29:13.170 --> 00:29:17.730
My friend, Michael Kors,
is one of the number

00:29:17.730 --> 00:29:19.420
one designers in America today.

00:29:19.420 --> 00:29:23.340
But he has a big presence
in Macy's, along with Coach,

00:29:23.340 --> 00:29:26.880
selling luxury handbags,
accessories, shoes,

00:29:26.880 --> 00:29:28.140
and fashion.

00:29:28.140 --> 00:29:32.220
And I really believe that
they're leading the way.

00:29:32.220 --> 00:29:33.990
I like being on that bandwagon.

00:29:33.990 --> 00:29:35.656
I think it's very important.

00:29:35.656 --> 00:29:36.430
Thank you.

00:29:36.430 --> 00:29:37.570
Thank you.

00:29:37.570 --> 00:29:39.070
Hi, Tommy.

00:29:39.070 --> 00:29:40.240
Hi.

00:29:40.240 --> 00:29:44.710
Going back to that point in your
life, when your accountant came

00:29:44.710 --> 00:29:46.910
to you and said that you're
going to go bankrupt,

00:29:46.910 --> 00:29:48.326
what did you say
to yourself to be

00:29:48.326 --> 00:29:51.250
able to still feel that you
could persevere and continue

00:29:51.250 --> 00:29:52.312
with your dream?

00:29:52.312 --> 00:29:54.020
Do you want to know
what I said at first?

00:29:54.020 --> 00:29:55.210
Yeah.

00:29:55.210 --> 00:29:58.150
Oh, shit.

00:29:58.150 --> 00:30:00.970
Oh, no.

00:30:00.970 --> 00:30:05.230
See, my father was a
watchmaker, jeweler.

00:30:05.230 --> 00:30:06.280
My mother was a nurse.

00:30:06.280 --> 00:30:08.230
And we had nine children.

00:30:08.230 --> 00:30:10.960
So that sort of tells
you that I couldn't

00:30:10.960 --> 00:30:17.170
go knocking on my parents'
door to get a loan.

00:30:17.170 --> 00:30:20.260
I really had to rethink my life.

00:30:20.260 --> 00:30:22.210
And I had to decide
at that point in time,

00:30:22.210 --> 00:30:24.220
should I go back to school?

00:30:24.220 --> 00:30:27.580
Should I continue on?

00:30:27.580 --> 00:30:31.890
I was so passionate
about what I was doing.

00:30:31.890 --> 00:30:33.470
I decided to continue on.

00:30:33.470 --> 00:30:35.360
And I learned about the law.

00:30:35.360 --> 00:30:38.060
I learned about the fact that,
if you are Chapter 11, which

00:30:38.060 --> 00:30:42.470
is a form of bankruptcy, you can
stay in business as long as you

00:30:42.470 --> 00:30:47.870
pay your creditors off,
and as long as you really

00:30:47.870 --> 00:30:49.710
operate on a cash basis.

00:30:49.710 --> 00:30:51.650
So I kept in
business at the time,

00:30:51.650 --> 00:30:53.900
and then built the business
back up to the point

00:30:53.900 --> 00:30:56.750
where I could sell
it, take that money,

00:30:56.750 --> 00:31:00.650
and become my own manufacturing
designer brand, which

00:31:00.650 --> 00:31:03.740
was tiny at the time, but
I had visions and dreams

00:31:03.740 --> 00:31:05.030
of it growing.

00:31:05.030 --> 00:31:07.490
And my dreams did come true.

00:31:07.490 --> 00:31:09.460
So I do believe
dreams do come true.

00:31:12.100 --> 00:31:12.850
All right.

00:31:12.850 --> 00:31:15.080
Thank you so much
for coming today.

00:31:15.080 --> 00:31:18.490
I appreciate you sharing your
transparency and being real.

00:31:18.490 --> 00:31:21.640
I know a lot of us students
at the University of Arizona

00:31:21.640 --> 00:31:23.410
have dreams.

00:31:23.410 --> 00:31:26.320
And you've shown us that
they are obtainable.

00:31:26.320 --> 00:31:27.940
So thank you.

00:31:27.940 --> 00:31:32.050
But mine is more or less just a
comment that I wanted to make.

00:31:32.050 --> 00:31:33.850
On behalf of all of
the students attending

00:31:33.850 --> 00:31:35.770
the Global Retail
Conference, we want

00:31:35.770 --> 00:31:37.810
to say thank you for
all of you for allowing

00:31:37.810 --> 00:31:40.210
us to be a fly on the wall.

00:31:40.210 --> 00:31:43.210
We take away great insight
on brand development,

00:31:43.210 --> 00:31:45.920
building brand equity,
and most importantly,

00:31:45.920 --> 00:31:48.220
understanding the
forever-changing environment

00:31:48.220 --> 00:31:50.460
and challenges
faced by retailers.

00:31:50.460 --> 00:31:52.254
And for that, we want
to say thank you.

00:31:52.254 --> 00:31:53.555
Thank you very much.

00:31:53.555 --> 00:31:54.555
It's a great compliment.

00:31:54.555 --> 00:31:57.245
[APPLAUSE]

00:31:57.245 --> 00:31:59.620
Thank you.

00:31:59.620 --> 00:32:02.820
Tommy, what are the
contemporary trends

00:32:02.820 --> 00:32:05.400
in American casual
wear and denim,

00:32:05.400 --> 00:32:07.890
and how are they different
around the globe?

00:32:07.890 --> 00:32:10.680
What are other cultures' tastes?

00:32:10.680 --> 00:32:13.680
Well, I think they vary
somewhat around the globe.

00:32:13.680 --> 00:32:17.040
Not tremendously, because
the people in Japan

00:32:17.040 --> 00:32:19.410
are wearing the same
styles that they're

00:32:19.410 --> 00:32:21.750
wearing in Paris, that they're
wearing in Minneapolis.

00:32:21.750 --> 00:32:26.580
But I really believe that there
are nuances in different areas.

00:32:26.580 --> 00:32:29.940
The preppy look in some
areas is not the same

00:32:29.940 --> 00:32:31.530
as it is in the states.

00:32:31.530 --> 00:32:35.850
In Italy, it's much brighter
and much more slender.

00:32:35.850 --> 00:32:38.160
In France, it's a
little bit more staid

00:32:38.160 --> 00:32:40.920
and a little bit more starched.

00:32:40.920 --> 00:32:45.720
I think that it
depends on the region.

00:32:45.720 --> 00:32:48.830
And it depends on even
the weights of the fabric.

00:32:48.830 --> 00:32:52.050
Our business in Germany is much
different than our business

00:32:52.050 --> 00:32:53.100
in Spain.

00:32:53.100 --> 00:32:56.040
The Germans like
heavier, darker fabrics.

00:32:56.040 --> 00:32:59.760
The customer in
Spain would prefer

00:32:59.760 --> 00:33:01.170
something lighter and brighter.

00:33:01.170 --> 00:33:04.080
So we mold and shape
to the territory.

00:33:04.080 --> 00:33:06.560
And we do that with My Macy's.

00:33:06.560 --> 00:33:10.080
Terry developed a program
called My Macy's, whereby,

00:33:10.080 --> 00:33:12.930
in Texas, the stores might
want something different

00:33:12.930 --> 00:33:15.210
than they would want in Boston.

00:33:15.210 --> 00:33:17.310
And I think that's
really a great way

00:33:17.310 --> 00:33:22.140
to plan and develop a
business, because you're really

00:33:22.140 --> 00:33:24.790
responding to the
customers' needs.

00:33:24.790 --> 00:33:26.790
But from a fashion
standpoint, I think

00:33:26.790 --> 00:33:31.620
we're all on the same track
of what is fashionable,

00:33:31.620 --> 00:33:33.030
what is now.

00:33:33.030 --> 00:33:35.390
But I think, from
a fit standpoint,

00:33:35.390 --> 00:33:38.070
a color, a fabric
standpoint, it does vary.

00:33:41.144 --> 00:33:42.185
And it's a good question.

00:33:46.320 --> 00:33:46.820
Yes.

00:33:46.820 --> 00:33:47.320
Yes.

00:33:47.320 --> 00:33:48.625
I work for a brand design firm.

00:33:48.625 --> 00:33:50.750
And I just wanted to say,
first of all, that I love

00:33:50.750 --> 00:33:53.410
your American-- I'm over here.

00:33:53.410 --> 00:33:54.216
Right over here.

00:33:54.216 --> 00:33:54.716
All right.

00:33:54.716 --> 00:33:55.910
All right.

00:33:55.910 --> 00:33:57.010
OK.

00:33:57.010 --> 00:33:58.460
The speaker is over here, so--

00:33:58.460 --> 00:34:00.200
I'm sorry.

00:34:00.200 --> 00:34:01.850
I love your American
Family campaign.

00:34:01.850 --> 00:34:02.960
I think it's fantastic.

00:34:02.960 --> 00:34:03.606
Thank you.

00:34:03.606 --> 00:34:05.480
One of the best things
about it and, I think,

00:34:05.480 --> 00:34:10.177
about your brand-- its essence
is the styling of the clothes,

00:34:10.177 --> 00:34:11.510
not just the clothes themselves.

00:34:11.510 --> 00:34:14.750
I'm wondering how you make sure
that that reaches the store

00:34:14.750 --> 00:34:19.100
level, and that the styling
itself is translating.

00:34:19.100 --> 00:34:23.980
That's a very difficult
proposition, making sure

00:34:23.980 --> 00:34:27.100
that the stores look
like the advertising.

00:34:27.100 --> 00:34:30.550
Well, we're talking about
hundreds and hundreds

00:34:30.550 --> 00:34:32.650
of designs every season.

00:34:32.650 --> 00:34:36.639
And it's up to the buyer and
the buyers in these stores

00:34:36.639 --> 00:34:38.020
to select.

00:34:38.020 --> 00:34:40.330
And sometimes,
they may not think

00:34:40.330 --> 00:34:42.730
that one of the
jackets in the ad

00:34:42.730 --> 00:34:46.659
would be appropriate for their
consumer because of the climate

00:34:46.659 --> 00:34:47.460
or whatever.

00:34:47.460 --> 00:34:50.110
But we try our best
to make sure that what

00:34:50.110 --> 00:34:53.980
we show in the advertising
ends up on the selling floor.

00:34:53.980 --> 00:34:57.430
And sometimes, it ends up on
the selling floor in smaller

00:34:57.430 --> 00:35:00.190
quantities and sells
out immediately,

00:35:00.190 --> 00:35:05.710
which prompts us to redesign
the same item with, maybe,

00:35:05.710 --> 00:35:08.440
a nuance or two for
the next season.

00:35:08.440 --> 00:35:10.000
But we try very
hard to make sure

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:12.217
that whatever is in the
advertising shows up

00:35:12.217 --> 00:35:12.800
in the stores.

00:35:16.635 --> 00:35:17.625
Thank you.

00:35:22.080 --> 00:35:23.070
You're welcome.

00:35:27.030 --> 00:35:28.170
Thank you very much.

00:35:28.170 --> 00:35:29.670
[APPLAUSE]

00:35:29.670 --> 00:35:31.520
Thank you.

